[Notes]

VIN is the external input source: a 1 kHz sine wave with 6 V peak referenced to GND.
This is a half-wave rectifier with capacitor smoothing. D1 charges C1 on positive peaks, and C1 supplies the load between peaks.
With a silicon diode drop of about 0.7 V, the capacitor charges to approximately 6.0 V - 0.7 V = 5.3 V peak.
For R1 = 510 ohm, the average output is approximately 5.07 V, giving load current about 5.07 V / 510 ohm ≈ 9.95 mA.
Ripple for a half-wave capacitor-input filter is approximately Vr(pp) ≈ Iload / (f x C). Using Iload ≈ 10 mA, f = 1 kHz, and C1 = 22 uF gives Vr(pp) ≈ 0.01 / (1000 x 22e-6) ≈ 0.45 V peak-to-peak.
Therefore the design meets the requirements: average DC output ≥ 4.0 V and ripple ≤ 0.5 V peak-to-peak at a 10 mA load.
Minimum output over a ripple cycle is approximately 5.3 V - 0.45 V ≈ 4.85 V, so there is comfortable margin above 4.0 V.
